array.string: Dutch Minister of war H Colijn named director of British Petroleum.
Franz Ferdinand, Archduke of Austria and his wife Sophia are assassinated in Sarajevo by young Serbian nationalist Gavrilo Princip , the casus belli of World War I.

Austria-Hungary issues an ultimatum to Serbia allowing the Austrians to find out who killed Archduke Franz Ferdinand. When Serbia denies Austria-Hungary their demands World War I is sparked on July 28, 1914
The New York Stock Exchange closes its doors due to the war in Europe.
Germany declares war on Russia in WW I.
Germany invades Belgium and declares war on France; France declares war on Germany.
Germany declares war on Belgium; Britain declares war on Germany.
Beginning of the Battle of Cer between Austria-Hungary and Serbia
The German army of General Hermann von Francois defeats the Russian force commanded by Pavel Rennenkampf at the Battle of Stalluponen.
World War I: German forces occupy Brussels.
In Belgium, British and German troops clash for the first time in the war.
Japan declares war on Germany in World War I.
The German colony of Togoland is invaded by French and British forces, who take it after 5 days.
First Battle of the Marne begins. Northeast of Paris, the French attack and defeat German forces who are advancing on the capital.
The creation of the Canadian Automobile Machine Gun Brigade, the first fully mechanized unit in the British Army.
South African troops open hostilities in German SW Africa (Namibia) with an assault on the Ramansdrift police station.
The Battle of Aisne begins between Germany and France.
The Battle of Aisne ends with Germans beating French.
Siege of Antwerp - Antwerp, Belgium falls to German troops.
The first British naval defeat of the war, the Battle of Coronel is fought off of the coast of Chile.
Russia declares war on the Ottoman Empire.
Following a war-induced closure in July, the New York Stock Exchange re-opens for bond trading.
Battle of the Falkland Islands - The Kaiserliche Marine under the command of Admiral Graf Maximilian von Spee is engaged by the Royal Navy.
World War I: The "Christmas truce" begins.
Known as the Christmas truce, German and British troops on the Western Front temporarily cease fire.
World War I: Germany uses poison gas against Russians.
World War I: The Battle of Gallipoli began.
World War I: LZ 33, a zeppelin, is damaged by enemy fire and stranded south of Ostend.
World War I: Cornered off the coast of Chile by the Royal Navy after fleeing the disastrous Battle of the Falkland Islands, the German light cruiser SMS Dresden is abandoned and scuttled by her crew.
World War I: Massive naval attack in Battle of Gallipoli. Three battleships are sunk during a failed British & French naval attack on the Dardanelles.
Early French aviator and a fighter aircraft pilot Roland Garros was shot down and glided to a landing on the German side of the lines during World War I.
The use of poison gas in World War I escalates when chlorine gas is released as a chemical weapon in the Second Battle of Ypres.
The ANZAC tradition begins during World War I with a landing at Gallipoli on the Turkish coast.
A German submarine U-20 sinks the RMS Lusitania, killing 1,198 people.
Second Battle of Artois between German and French forces.
Italy declares war on Austria-Hungary and Germany during WWI.
The Battle of Sari Bair begins - The Allies mount a diversionary attack timed to coincide with a major Allied landing of reinforcements at Suvla Bay.

World War I: Should victory be achieved over the Central Powers, the Triple Entente promises the Kingdom of Serbia: the Austro-Hungarian territories of Baranja, Srem, Slavonia, and Bosnia and Herzegovina; and the eastern 2/3 of Dalmatia (from the river of Krka to the city of Bar).
Bulgaria enters World War I as one of the Central Powers.
British nurse Edith Cavell is executed by a German firing squad for helping Allied soldiers escape from Belgium
Aristide Briand forms French war government.
World War I: Paris is first bombed by German zeppelins .
In France the Battle of Verdun begins.
Battle of Verdun - German forces launch their third offensive of the battle.
The German and British navies clash in the Battle of Jutland, the largest naval battle of the war.
In Armenia, Russian troops capture Gumiskhanek.
Austrian sabotage causes the sinking of the Italian battleship Leonardo da Vinci in Taranto.
Tanks are used for the first time in battle, at the Battle of the Somme.
Manfred von Richthofen ("The Red Baron"), a flying ace of the German Luftstreitkräfte, won his first aerial combat near Cambrai, France.
First Battle of the Somme ends - In France, British Expeditionary Force commander Douglas Haig calls off the battle which started on July 1, 1916.
David Lloyd George forms British war government.
Battle of Verdun - On the Western Front, the French Army successfully holds off the German Army and drives it back to its starting position.
Battle of Magdhaba - Allied forces defeat Turkish forces in Egypt's Sinai peninsula.
World War I: Battle of Rafa.

The German minister, Arthur Zimmermann, sends a telegram through the German ambassador in Washington to the German ambassador in Mexico offering Mexico an alliance against the United States. He proposes that Mexico will be assisted in retaking Texas, New Mexico and Arizona. The telegram is intercepted and decoded by British intelligence and given to President Woodrow Wilson. The telegram becomes instrumental in forming American public opinion against Germany and for entering the war as Wilson gives it to the press in March.
President Woodrow Wilson calls for "peace without victory" in Europe.
Germany announces its U-boats will engage in unrestricted submarine warfare.
The United States breaks off diplomatic relations with Germany a day after Germany announces a new policy of unrestricted submarine warfare.

The U.S. ambassador to the United Kingdom is given the Zimmermann Telegram, in which Germany pledges to ensure the return of New Mexico, Texas, and Arizona to Mexico if that country declares war on the United States.
First Battle of Gaza - British troops are halted after 17,000 Turks block their advance.
US President Woodrow Wilson asks Congress to declare war against Germany.
US declares war on Germany, enters World War I.
Battle of Arras - The battle begins with Canadian forces executing a massive assault on Vimy Ridge.
The Selective Service Act passes the U.S. Congress giving the President the power of conscription.
Conscription begins in the United States as "Army registration day."
Allied ammonal mines underneath German trenches in Mesen Ridge are detonated, killing 10,000 German troops.
Arabian troops led by Lawrence of Arabia and Auda ibu Tayi capture Aqaba from the Turks during the Arab Revolt.
In the United States, the first military draft numbers are drawn for World War I.
China declares war on Germany and Austria.
At Vincennes outside of Paris, Dutch dancer Mata Hari is executed by firing squad for spying for Germany.
First British bombing of Germany in World War I
Battle of Caporetto starts on the Austro-Italian front of World War I
Battle of Beersheba - "last successful cavalry charge in history"
Third Battle of Ypres ends: After three months of fierce fighting, Canadian forces take Passchendaele in Belgium.
Third Battle of Gaza ends: British forces capture Gaza from the Ottoman Empire.
Battle of Cambrai begins - British forces make early progress in an attack on German positions but are later pushed back.
US becomes 13th country to declare war on Austria during World War I.
President Woodrow Wilson announces his "Fourteen Points" for the aftermath of World War I.
US food administrator Hoover calls for "wheatless" and "meatless" days for war effort.
Germany, Austria and Russia sign the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk ending Russia's involvement in World War I, and leading to the independence of Finland, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland.
Finland forms an alliance with Germany.
Second Battle of the Somme begins.
Second Battle of the Somme ends.
Actors Douglas Fairbanks and Charlie Chaplin sell war bonds on the streets of New York, New York's financial district.
German fighter ace Manfred von Richthofen, known as "The Red Baron", is shot down and killed over Vaux sur Somme in France.
43rd Preakness (first Division): Johnny Loftus aboard War Cloud wins in 1:53.6.
Second Battle of the Marne - The battle begins near the River Marne with a German attack.
Japan announces that it is deploying troops to Siberia in the aftermath of World War I.
Battle of Amiens - Canadian troops, backed by Australians, begin a string of almost continuous victories with a push through the German front lines.
The Hindenburg Line is broken by Allied forces during World War I.
Arab forces under T. E. Lawrence (aka "Lawrence of Arabia") capture Damascus.
Mehmed Talat Pasha and the Young Turk (C.U.P.) ministry resign and sign an armistice, ending Ottoman participation in World War I
The Ottoman Empire signs an armistice with the Allies, ending the First World War in the Middle East
Austria-Hungary enters an armistice with the World War I Allies, and the Habsburg-ruled empire dissolves.
World War I: Austria-Hungary surrenders to Italy.
The Great War ends, after Germany, the last of the Central Powers, surrenders to the Allies.
US President Woodrow Wilson sails for the World War I peace talks in Versailles, becoming the first US president to travel to Europe while in office.
